\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \lim_{\omega_{f}\rightarrow\infty}\frac{dg}{d\omega_{f}}\left(\omega_{f}\right)=\infty}$
\end_inset

 nos implica que 
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \lim_{\omega_{f}\rightarrow\infty}g\left(\omega_{f}\right)=\infty}$
\end_inset

 y, en consecuencia, 
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \lim_{\omega_{f}\rightarrow\infty}a\left(\omega_{f}\right)=0}<a\left(\omega_{f,r}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Por otra parte, como 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{f,r}$
\end_inset

 es un cero simple, y sabemos que 
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \lim_{\omega_{f}\rightarrow\infty}\frac{dg}{d\omega_{f}}\left(\omega_{f}\right)=\infty>0}$
\end_inset

, debe ser 
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \frac{da}{d\omega_{f}}\left(\omega_{f}\right)<0\;\forall\omega_{f}>\omega_{f,r}}$
